===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A belief, judgment or perspective that a [[person]] has formed, either through [[objective]] or [[subjective]] reasoning, about a [[topic]], [[issue]], person or thing.
#: {{ux|en|I would like to know your '''opinions''' on the new filing system.}}
#: {{ux|en|In my '''opinion''', white chocolate is better than milk chocolate.}}
#: {{ux|en|Every man is a fool in some man's '''opinion'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|We invite you to state your '''opinions''' about the suggestions.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1891|{{w|Oscar Wilde}}|The Critic as Artist|text=Truth, in matters of religion, is simply the '''opinion''' that has survived.}}
# The judgment or sentiment which the mind forms of persons or things; [[estimation]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|I|vii|line=32|text=I have bought golden '''opinions''' from all sorts of people.}}
#* {{RQ:South Twelve Sermons|text=Friendship {{...}} gives a man a peculiar right and claim to the good '''opinion''' of his friend.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Favorable estimation; hence, consideration; reputation; fame; public sentiment or esteem.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 4-1|V|iv|line=47|text=Thou hast redeemed thy lost '''opinion'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Milton History|passage=This gained Agricola much '''opinion''', who {{...}} had made such early progress into laborious {{...}} enterprises.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Obstinacy in holding to one's belief or impression; opiniativeness; conceitedness.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Love's Labour's Lost|V|i|line=5|text=Your reasons at / dinner have been sharp and sententious, pleasant / without scurrility, witty without affection, audacious / without impudency, learned without '''opinion''', and / strange without heresy.}}
# The formal decision, or expression of views, of a judge, an umpire, a doctor, or other party officially called upon to consider and decide upon a matter or point submitted.
# {{lb|en|European Union law}} a [[judicial]] opinion delivered by an Advocate General to the European Court of Justice where he or she proposes a legal solution to the cases for which the court is responsible

